        "id": 2449091,
        "name": "Peter Moy",
        "username": "P_Moy",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/p/a9a28c/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2018-07-16T14:11:20.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Slightly dark gold color.  Intense nose of roasted nuts, citrus, apples, flowers and minerals soar from the glass.  This smelled like a cross between a Meursault and a Puligny.  Round and creamy in the mouth with a satiny texture that was utterly sensuous.  Palate staining flavors of citrus and minerals lead into a long finish, with a late note of spice that adds complexity.  Great acidity and balance.  This saw two hours in a decanter.</p>\n<p>Incredible quality, and a good bet to at least equal if not surpass the premier crus and grand crus of other producers.  This and the other two Auxey wines in the d\u2019Auvenay stable used to be more widely available at decent prices, but no longer.  One can only wonder what the premier and grand cru wines of d\u2019Auvenay must taste like.</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 6,
        "updated_at": "2022-06-03T05:14:41.062Z",
        "reply_count": 0,
